'''Lu<U+00ED>s Alves de Lima e Silva''', the '''Duke of Caxias''' ({{IPA-pt|ka<U+02C8><U+0283>i<U+0250>s}} or {{IPA-pt|ka<U+02C8><U+0283>i<U+0250><U+0283>|}}; August 25, 1803 <U+2013> May 7, 1880), nicknamed "The Peacemaker"{{sfn|Bento|2003|p=xi}} and "Iron Duke",{{sfn|Moraes|2003|p=28}} was a monarchist, military officer and politician of the [[Empire of Brazil]]. He was one of the main leaders of the [[Conservative Party (Brazil)|Conservative Party]] and on more than one occasion served as [[Prime Minister of Brazil|President of the Council of Ministers]] (Prime minister). Considered one of the most important heroes in [[Military history of Brazil|Brazilian military history]], Caxias fought in the [[Cisplatine War]], the [[War of the Ragamuffins]], [[Platine War]], and, most notably, in the [[Paraguayan War]]. He was the only Brazilian not related to the [[House of Braganza]] to receive the title of [[Duke]], and the only Duke to be created in the reign of Emperor Pedro II. Caxias entered the military while in adolescence, and rapidly rose to the ranks of [[General]] and [[Baron]], subsequently becoming [[Marshal]], [[Count]], [[Marquis]], [[Senator]], and [[Aide-de-Camp]] to the Emperor. He was twice [[Minister of War]] and also President of the Council, exerting great political influence as a conservative leader. Caxias was superseded as commander of the Brazilian Forces by the Count d'Eu after the capture of [[Asunci<U+00F3>n]], and received the title of [[Duke]] in 1869. The "Day of the Soldier" is an annual celebration that occurs on his birthday, August 25. The cities of [[Duque de Caxias]] and [[Caxias do Sul]] are named in his honor. He is honoured as the Patron of the Brazilian Army.

==Early years==
===Family background===
The earliest known [[Patrilineality|patrilineal ancestor]] of the Duke of Caxias is his great-grandfather, Jo<U+00E3>o da Silva da Fonseca. He was a sergeant major (equivalent to a major in today's army) assigned to an artillery regiment in [[Lagos, Portugal|Lagos]], a town in the [[Algarve]] of southern [[Portugal]].{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=50<U+2013>51}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=4}} He may have been a wealthy merchant and his position as an officer in his regiment may explain why his eldest son began his career with the rank of ''alferes'' (the modern equivalent of [[Second Lieutenant]]), a privilege open to few in Portugal's highly hierarchical society.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=51}} Jo<U+00E3>o da Silva had two sons and two daughters. Both male children embarked upon a military career.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=53, 61}} The brothers had neither noble rank nor noble ancestry{{ref label|specialnotes2|B|none}} and lacked patrons in an environment in which advancement depended upon exchanges of favors and family connections.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=52<U+2013>53, 61}} Rather than pursuing a career in the Portuguese homeland, far better opportunities for rising through the ranks were available in defending the far-flung Portuguese colonies.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=58}}

The eldest son, Francisco de Lima da Silva (later Lima e Silva),{{ref label|specialnotes1|A|none}} brought his younger brother Jos<U+00E9> Joaquim de Lima da Silva to Brazil, [[Colonial Brazil|then a Portuguese colony]], in 1767.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=62}} The two settled in [[Rio de Janeiro]], capital of both the [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|Rio de Janeiro]] [[captaincy]] (later province) and of the Viceroyalty of Brazil. They lived for several years in the South American colony and fought against the Spaniards on its southern frontiers.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=72}} Francisco de Lima was retired and returned to Portugal in 1777, where he died<U+2014>unmarried<U+2014>two years later.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=73<U+2013>74}}

His younger brother, Jos<U+00E9> Joaquim, opted to stay in Brazil.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=74}} He slowly advanced through the ranks{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=75}} and in 1785 managed to enter into an advantageous marriage to Joana Maria da Fonseca Costa, a member of an influential family who had resided in Rio de Janeiro since the 17th century.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=82<U+2013>83}} Joaquim named his first-born son, Francisco de Lima da Silva, after his older brother.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=85}} In 1801, Francisco was married to Mariana C<U+00E2>ndido de Oliveira Belo, whose prominent family was originally from the captaincy of [[Minas Gerais]].{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=85<U+2013>87}} The eldest male child of Francisco and Mariana was the future Duke of Caxias.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=85}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=6}}

===Birth and childhood===
Lu<U+00ED>s Alves de Lima e Silva was born on 25 August 1803 to Francisco de Lima e Silva and Mariana C<U+00E2>ndido de Oliveira Belo.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=4}}{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=107}} His birthplace was a farm called S<U+00E3>o Paulo (today within the city of [[Duque de Caxias]]) located in the captaincy of Rio de Janeiro.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=4}}{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=108}} Lu<U+00ED>s Alves' godparents were his paternal grandfather, Jos<U+00E9> Joaquim, and his maternal grandmother, Ana Quit<U+00E9>ria Joaquina.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=108}}

Although he would eventually become one of the most important figures in [[History of Brazil|Brazilian history]], there is only scant information regarding Lu<U+00ED>s Alves' life prior to age 36, at which point he was chosen to suppress the [[Balaiada]] rebellion.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=33}} It is known that Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was the second eldest child (but first son) out of ten children to his parents.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=108, 565}} His early years were spent on the S<U+00E3>o Paulo farm owned by his maternal grandfather, and namesake, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves de Freitas.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=108}} The young boy may have been initially schooled at home, as was common then. He also may have learned to read and write from his grandmother, Ana Quit<U+00E9>ria.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=109}}

The [[Transfer of the Portuguese Court to Brazil|arrival of the Portuguese Royal Family]] in Rio de Janeiro in 1808 changed the lives of the Lima family.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=90}} King [[Dom (title)|Dom]] [[John VI of Portugal|Jo<U+00E3>o VI]] embarked upon a series of wars of conquest which resulted in the expansion of Brazil's territory with the annexation of [[Cisplatina]] to the south and of [[French Guiana]] to the north.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=92}} By 1818, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves' relatives had been ennobled. His grandfather, Jos<U+00E9> Joaquim became a member of the [[Order of Christ (Portugal)|Order of Christ]] and ''fidalgo cavaleiro da Casa Real'' (knight noble of the Royal House).{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=93}} His father, Francisco, and uncles were also granted honors.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=93<U+2013>94}} Within a span of two generations, the Lima family had risen from mere commoners into the ranks of Portugal's untitled nobility.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=93<U+2013>95}}

===Military education===

In 1808, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was enlisted at the age of 5 as a cadet in the 1st Regiment of Infantry of Rio de Janeiro.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=109}} Historian Adriana Barreto de Souza explained that this did "not mean that he began to serve as a child, the connection to the regiment was simply honorific", a perquisite open to Lu<U+00ED>s Alves as the son of a military officer.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=4}}{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=109}} This infantry regiment was informally known as the "Lima [family] Regiment" because so many members of the family served in it, including Lu<U+00ED>s Alves' father and grandfather.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=93, 109}}

In 1811, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves moved with his parents from his grandparents' farm to Rio de Janeiro and was enrolled at the ''Semin<U+00E1>rio S<U+00E3>o Joaquim'' (Saint Joachim's School).{{sfn|Bento|2003|pp=27<U+2013>28}}{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=109}} Seven years later, in 1818, he was admitted into the [[Academia Militar das Agulhas Negras|Royal Military Academy]] as an ''alferes'' (equivalent to a Second Lieutenant today).{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=11}}{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=109}} The next year he was promoted to the rank of Lieutenant (nowadays First Lieutenant).{{sfn|Bento|2003|p=28}}

In the Royal Military Academy he followed the course of Infantry.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=113}} To graduate as an infantryman, he was supposed to take classes of the 1st and 5th year, which he did, in 1818 and 1819, respectively.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=113<U+2013>114}} Although the entire course (which ran from the 1st to 7th year) was only mandatory to artillerymen and engineers, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves opted to take classes of the 2nd year in 1820 and of the 3th year in 1821.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=114}} He took classes that ranged from arithmetic, algebra and geometry to [[Military tactics|tactics]], [[Military strategy|strategy]], camping, fortification in campaign and terrain reconnaissance.{{ref label|specialnotes3|C|none}} Albeit an accomplished student, the young Lieutenant was often reprimanded for [[bullying]] newbies.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=114, 120<U+2013>121}}

==Between family and loyalty to the crown==
===Independence of Brazil===
{{main|Independence of Brazil}}
Lu<U+00ED>s Alves would normally have begun his 4th year classes at the Royal Military Academy sometime in March 1822.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=124}} Lu<U+00ED>s Alves dropped out of the academy in December 1821 and enlisted in the 1st Fusilier Battalion.{{sfn|Bento|2003|p=28}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=11}} Prince Dom Pedro, son and heir of King Jo<U+00E3>o&nbsp;VI, had just embarked upon the struggle against Portugal that led to the independence of Brazil on 7 September 1822.{{sfn|Barman|1988|pp=74<U+2013>96}} The Prince was later acclaimed Dom Pedro&nbsp;I, first Brazilian emperor, on 12 October.{{sfn|Barman|1988|pp=100<U+2013>101}} Those Brazilian and Portuguese forces who remained loyal to Portugal refused to accept this outcome, which led to a war fought on several fronts across Brazil's provinces.{{sfn|Barman|1988|pp=104<U+2013>106}}

On 18 January 1823, Pedro&nbsp;I created the "Emperor's Battalion", an elite infantry unit composed of men handpicked by himself.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=12}} One of those selected for the new battalion was Lu<U+00ED>s Alves. He was named as [[adjutant]] to the company's commander, who happened to be his uncle, Colonel Jos<U+00E9> Joaquim de Lima e Silva.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=13}} The Emperor's Battalion was sent to the province of [[Bahia]] (in the Brazilian northeast) on 28 January.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=17}} Upon arrival, it was placed,  along with other troops, under the command of French Brigadier General [[Pierre Labatut]]. The Brazilian Imperial forces besieged Bahia's capital, [[Salvador]], which was held by the Portuguese.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=17}} During the siege, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves fought in at least three attacks (on 28 March, 3 May and 3 June) against Portuguese positions around Salvador, all successful.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=18}}{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=137}} In the engagement on 28 March, he stormed entrenched Portuguese positions in a bayonet assault.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=18}} In the final battle on 3 June (which was also the last land combat in this theater of war) he led a charge, with sword drawn, on an enemy bunker.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=18}}

During the Bahia campaign, high ranking officers mutinied against Commander-in-Chief Labatut, who was taken prisoner and sent back to Rio de Janeiro.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=131}} Lu<U+00ED>s Alves' uncle Joaquim (the commander of the Emperor's Battalion) was almost certainly part of the conspiracy and was chosen by the officers to replace Labatut. It is unknown if Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was also involved.{{ref label|specialnotes4|D|none}} It is probable that he did not participate since, unlike his uncle and other relatives in the army, he was not rewarded with any [[Officer (armed forces)|commission]] by the conspirators.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=132}} The campaign resumed, and the Portuguese withdrew from Salvador and set sail back to Portugal. On 2 July. the victorious Brazilians entered the city.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=19}}{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=133}} The Emperor's Battalion returned to Rio de Janeiro, and Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was later promoted to Captain in early 1824.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=20}}{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=137}}

===Cisplatine War and father's betrayal===
{{See also|Cisplatine War}}
The Portuguese garrison in [[Montevideo]], which was the capital of [[Cisplatina]] (then Brazil's southernmost province), was the last to surrender.{{sfn|Barman|1988|p=107}} In 1825, secessionists in the province rebelled. The [[United Provinces of South America]] (later [[Argentina]]) attempted to annex Cisplatina. Brazil declared war on the United Provinces, triggering the [[Cisplatine War]].{{sfn|Barman|1988|p=139}} The Emperor's Battalion, to which Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was still attached, was sent to guard Montevideo, then besieged by rebel forces. Lu<U+00ED>s Alves fought in engagements against the insurgents during 1827 (7 February, 5 July, 7 July, 14 July, 5 August and 7 August).{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=23}}

The dates are unknown for two other actions in which Lu<U+00ED>s Alves participated. The first of these was a raid in which he led a few soldiers against a docked corsair and its crew of 50 men. The Brazilian forces passed through enemy lines unnoticed and captured both the ship and its crew.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=23}} The second action was a night attack against a rebel position in which he managed to capture more than 30 enemy soldiers.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=23}}

During his stay in Montevideo, he met [[Mar<U+00ED>a <U+00C1>ngela Furriol Gonz<U+00E1>lez Luna]], of Spanish ancestry and daughter of Magdalena Gonz<U+00E1>lez Luna Zaias, Marchioness of Montes Claros.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=26}}{{sfn|Bento|2003|p=69}} How far their relationship progressed is unknown (if there was any relationship at all), but Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was infatuated with the young woman, who was often described as very beautiful.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=26<U+2013>27}} The war came to a disastrous end in 1828 with Brazil's relinquishment of Cisplatina, which became the independent nation of Uruguay.{{sfn|Barman|1988|p=151}} Nonetheless, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was promoted to the rank of major in late 1828.{{sfn|Bento|2003|p=28}}

Lu<U+00ED>s Alves returned to Rio de Janeiro and witnessed the increasing decline in Emperor Pedro&nbsp;I's political position. A growing opposition to Pedro&nbsp;I's policies eventually erupted into mass protests in the Field of Santana, in downtown Rio de Janeiro, on 6 April 1831. The situation grew more ominous when several military units joined the protests.{{sfn|Barman|1988|pp=158<U+2013>159}} Although forgiven by the Emperor, and even advanced by him despite their role in the plot against Labatut in 1823,{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=137}} Lu<U+00ED>s Alves's father and uncles betrayed the Pedro&nbsp;I and joined the rebellion.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=179}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=45}} The Emperor considered appointing Lu<U+00ED>s Alves to command the Emperor's Battalion and asked him which side he would choose.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=42}}

According to historian Francisco Doratioto, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves answered that "between the love of his father and his duty to the crown, he would stay with the latter."{{sfn|Doratioto|December 2003|p=62}} Lu<U+00ED>s Alves also volunteered to lead the militia against the rebel troops.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=43}} Pedro&nbsp;I expressed gratitude for his loyalty, but instead ordered him to lead the Emperor's Battalion to go to the Field of Santana and join the rebels.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=43}} Pedro&nbsp;I preferred abdication to civil war, and a few hours later, during the early hours of 7 April, he renounced the throne.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=46}} Many decades later, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves would say in the Brazilian Senate: "I marched along with the Emperor's Batallion to the Field of Santana, out of devotion to competent orders [from Pedro&nbsp;I]. I was not a revolutionary. I esteemed the Abdication. I judged that it would be of advantage to Brazil, but I did not concur directly or indirectly with it."{{sfn|Bento|2003|pp=28<U+2013>29}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=46}}

===Anarchy===
[[Image:Pedro II by heaton and rensburg.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=|[[Dom (title)|Dom]] [[Pedro II of Brazil|Pedro&nbsp;II]], Emperor of Brazil, around age 14, c.1840]]
A regency of three was elected to rule until the five-year-old Dom [[Pedro II of Brazil|Pedro&nbsp;II]] (Pedro&nbsp;I's son) reached the age of majority and the ability to rule in his own right. One of the regents chosen was Lu<U+00ED>s Alves' father, Francisco de Lima e Silva. According to historian Roderick J. Barman, "it was less Lima e Silva's character and talents than the hope that he could through his numerous relatives among the officer corps secure the loyalty of the army that prompted his selection."{{sfn|Barman|1988|p=162}} The hope that the army could be controlled was in vain. Historian C. H. Haring remarked: the "army, demoralized by the far from exemplary part it had played in the April Revolution [i.e. Pedro&nbsp;I's abdication], got entirely out of hand, and there were repeated mutinies in the garrisons. [...] Arrogant and undisciplined, believing that everything could be settled by resorts of arms, it became the ready tool of any popular agitator or demagogue, and often the source of riot and sedition."{{sfn|Haring|1969|p=46}}

The government severely reduced the size of the standing army contigent, and effectively replaced it with the newly created National Guard, a militia force.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=206<U+2013>208}} In October 1831, and without troops to command, officers (including Lu<U+00ED>s Alves) joined the Volunteer Officer-Soldiers Battalion, acting as soldiers.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=198}} Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was appointed commander of the Permanent Municipal Guard Corps, a police force in the city of Rio de Janeiro, in October 1832.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=223}}

On 6 January 1833, at age 29, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves married Ana Lu<U+00ED>sa de Loreto Carneiro Viana, aged 16 and younger sister of an Army officer friend. She was also a member of an aristocratic family of Rio de Janeiro. The marriage took place contrary to the wishes of the bride's mother, who saw Lu<U+00ED>s Alves and his family as upstarts. Newspapers connected to political enemies of his family took advantage of this disagreement to level serious, but unfounded, accusations against him, including that he had kidnapped Ana Lu<U+00ED>sa.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=240<U+2013>244}} Despite the invective, their marriage was a happy one{{sfn|Bento|2003|pp=63<U+2013>65}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|pp=52<U+2013>54}} and three children resulted: Lu<U+00ED>sa de Loreto Viana de Lima, Ana de Loreto Viana de Lima and Lu<U+00ED>s Alves de Lima e Silva, born in 1833, 1836 and 1847, respectively.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=565}} 

Around this time Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was appointed instructor in [[swordsmanship]] and [[horsemanship]] to the young Pedro&nbsp;II.{{sfn|Bento|2003|p=66}} Ties of duty had drawn the two men together, but a long-lasting friendship and personal devotion also developed. Although not a man of letters,{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=198}} Lu<U+00ED>s Alves had many other positive traits that Pedro&nbsp;II would come to appreciate. The future Duke of Caxias was considered a very reasonable{{sfn|Moraes|2003|pp=209<U+2013>210}} and honest person.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=545}} Historian Thomas Whigham described him as someone who "learned the art of giving orders early in life. Immaculate in his dress, he was soft spoken, polite, and smoothly in control of himself. He seemed to radiate calm composure and authority."{{sfn|Whigham|2002|p=62}} Pedro&nbsp;II would write about him many years later: "I believe Caxias to be loyal and my friend, especially because he is so little a politician."{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=170}} According to historian Heitor Lyra, he was "one of the rare, sincere and profoundly convicted monarchists and friends of the King [i.e., the Emperor] and of the Dynasty [the [[House of Braganza]]] He placed his sword not only in service to a united and strong Brazil, but also to a worthy and respected Monarch".{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=245}}

The Brazilian capital, followed by several provinces across the country, had meanwhile become a stage for countless rebellions and attempted coups. A republican secessionist rebellion that began in 1834 in the province of Rio Grande do Sul (whicht became known as the [[War of the Ragamuffins]]) was joined by an uncle of Lu<U+00ED>s Alves.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=281}} His father,{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=500}} and possibly another uncle (who was Minister of War at the time),{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=282}} secretly supported the rebellion. A younger brother of Lu<U+00ED>s Alves, also an Army officer, murdered a man in cold blood in a dispute over political grievances.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=251<U+2013>252}}

==Quelling rebellions==
===Balaiada===
{{main|Balaiada}}
[[Image:Baron of Caxias.png|thumb|200px|right|alt=|The then-Baron of Caxias around age 39, c.1842]]
By the late 1830s Lu<U+00ED>s Alves, as the commander of the Permanent Municipal Guard Corps, had managed to bring peace and order to Rio de Janeiro streets. This accomplishment was a result of Lu<U+00ED>s Alves' skills and his partnership with Rio chief of police, [[Eus<U+00E9>bio de Queir<U+00F3>s]]. Lu<U+00ED>s Alves' success brought the attention of Queir<U+00F3>s' political faction, the Coimbra bloc (the core what would later become the Conservative Party). The main leader of the Coimbra bloc, [[Bernardo Pereira de Vasconcelos]], who was also heading the Brazilian government, attempted to attract Lu<U+00ED>s Alves to his faction. A military officer in 19th century Brazil could not hope to advance through the ranks or be appointed to a prestigious command without being part of a political party. Thus Vasconcelos ordered Lu<U+00ED>s Alves to quell a rebellion in the province of [[Maranh<U+00E3>o]]. 

Maranh<U+00E3>o was one of several Brazilian provinces which had fallen in turmoil since Pedro I's abdication. It was located in Brazil's far north (nowadays regarded as Northeast) and was engulfed in a civil war between local political factions which became known as [[Balaiada]]. The struggle degenerated into banditism to the point that political grievances were long ignored and the original perpetrators (the local political factions) were eager to restore order. Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was appointed to the two highest civilian and military positions in the province: president (governor) and military commander (''comandante das armas''), thus giving him authority over the provincial National Guard and Army, respectively.

The groups of bandits that roamed the province were defeated in several battles and skirmishes. To Lu<U+00ED>s Alves' surprise, messages exchanged with the bandits' leaders revealed that not only they respected the authority of the child emperor, but also claimed that were fighting for him. He used this knowledge to pacify the province once the imperial government in Rio de Janeiro granted an amnesty to all involved in the provincial rebellion, including the bandits. The latter, or what still was left of any, surrended almost immediately once they learned that the Emperor himself had pardoned them. For his acchievement, Lu<U+00ED>s Alves was named Baron of Caxias. A rare honor, he was allowed to chose his noble name, which he did after [[Caxias (Maranh<U+00E3>o)|Caxias]], Maranh<U+00E3>o's second largest town, which had fallen in rebel hands and was reconquered by him.

===Liberal rebellions of 1842===
Being far away from the imperial capital did not prevent Lu<U+00ED>s Alves (or Caxias) from being dragged into Brazilian politics. During the entire time he spent in Maranh<U+00E3>o he was informed through letters by three persons of the last events, all of them eager to induce him into their political groups.  The first was Caxias' father, a member of what would become the Liberal Party. The second was Paulo Barbosa da Silva, then-steward in the Imperial Palace and a former colleague of Caxias in the Royal Military Academy, who belonged to the Courtier Faction. The third was [[Hon<U+00F3>rio Carneiro Le<U+00E3>o, Marquis of Paran<U+00E1>|Hon<U+00F3>rio Carneiro Le<U+00E3>o]] (later the Marquis of Paran<U+00E1>), a distant cousin of Caxias' wife (herself a granddaughter of Br<U+00E1>s Carneiro Le<U+00E3>o, kin to Hon<U+00F3>rio's father), of the Coimbra bloc.

When he returned from Maranh<U+00E3>o, Caxias saw the political milieu had changed. The Emperor had been prematurely declared of age and had appointed a cabinet formed by members of the Liberal Party and of the Courtier Faction, thus removing the Coimbra bloc from power. A crisis within the cabinet made Pedro II appoint a new one composed of members of the Coimbra bloc. In retaliation, the Liberals rebelled in the provinces of Rio de Janeiro, S<U+00E3>o Paulo and Minas Gerais. Caxias was ordered to quell the rebellion in S<U+00E3>o Paulo. Having defeated the rebels there, he marched to Minas Gerais and was once again successful. In the latter he was aided by a militia led by Carneiro Le<U+00E3>o, from which a strong friendship between both men would appear. Despite the mountaineous terrain on both provinces, quite different from the open fields in Cisplatina or the Amazon Rainforest jungles of Maranh<U+00E3>o, Caxias was extremely successful.

At least since his stay in Maranh<U+00E3>o, Caxias had grown closer to the Coimbra bloc. After the rebellions in S<U+00E3>o Paulo and Minas Gerais he was certainly among its ranks. He had become tired of seeing so many innocent civilian deaths caused by liberal rebellions since the 1830s. The Coimbra bloc, now self-styled "Party of Order", had principles more akin to Caxias since it supported liberalism, exceptionalism, state authority, and representative, parliamentary monarchy.{{sfn|Needell|2006|p=75}} Even though a member of a political party opposed to the Liberal Party, Caxias kept a respectful, even loving relationship toward his father.

