===Conciliation===
{{See also|September 6, 1853 cabinet}}
[[Image:Marquis of caxias.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=|Caxias around the age 52, c.1855]]
On 6 September 1853, Carneiro Le<U+00E3>o was appointed President of the Council of Ministers and charged with organizing a new cabinet. Emperor Pedro&nbsp;II wished to advance an ambitious plan, which became known as "the Conciliation".{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=182}} The goal of the Conciliation was to put an end to the periodic eruption of armed conflicts between political factions, such as had occurred in the ''Praieira'' rebellion. It had become usual for parties which had lost power in elections to attempt to forcibly seize back control. The Conciliation aimed to strengthen the role of parliament in settling the country's political disputes. Both parties would be required to agree to rise above partisan politics and instead devote themselves to the common good of the nation.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=162}}

The new President invited several Liberals to join the Conservative ranks and went so far as to name some as ministers. The new cabinet, albeit highly successful, was plagued from the beginning by strong opposition from Conservative Party members who repudiated the new recruits from the Liberal side, believing that these were mainly interested in gaining public offices, rather than truly supporting the party's goals.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=188}}{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|pp=167<U+2013>169}}{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=166}} Despite the mistrust, Carneiro Le<U+00E3>o managed to govern, demonstrating great resilience in fending off threats and overcoming obstacles and setbacks.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=162}}{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=166}}

After the sudden and unexpected death of Carneiro Le<U+00E3>o in September 1856, his cabinet only managed to survive him by a few months. The Emperor, although critical of the way the Conciliation had been implemented,{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=188}} had learned to appreciate its merits and was eager that it continue.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=192}}

===Rise of the Progressive League===
[[Image:Marquis of caxias c 1860.jpg|thumb|200px|left|alt=|Caxias around the age 58, c.1861]]
During the years following 1857, the cabinets quickly collapsed due to the lack of a majority in the Chamber of Deputies. The Conservative Party had split down the middle: on one side were the ultraconservatives, and on the other, dissident "Moderate Conservatives". In the wake of Carneiro Le<U+00E3>o's cabinet, a new generation of politicians had emerged, ambitious to gain more power in the Conservative Party. These men saw their path to the top ranks as being blocked by the Conservative elders, who would not easily relinquish control.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|pp=346, 370, 373, 376}} [[Jos<U+00E9> Paranhos, Viscount of Rio Branco|Jos<U+00E9> Paranhos]], a former colleague in the Conciliation Cabinet, managed to persuade Caxias to stay on the side of the ultraconservatives.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=369}}

The Liberal Party had declined since the end of the 1840s, and its remaining members saw an opportunity in the Conservative Party's fragmentation to return to national politics with renewed strength. They delivered a powerful blow to the government when they managed to win several seats in the Chamber of Deputies in 1860.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|pp=364<U+2013>365}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|pp=644<U+2013>645}} The Emperor asked Caxias to head a new cabinet on 2 March 1861.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=366}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|pp=660=661}} Caxias chose Paranhos as his Minister of Finance, and he soon became the Marquis's right hand. His influence became so great that the ministry became known as the "Caxias-Paranhos Cabinet".{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=366}}

The new government was faced with a major challenge: the Chamber of Deputies was divided into three groups: the ultraconservatives, the Moderates and the Liberals.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=369}} Paranhos and Caxias named men who were either ultraconservatives or Moderates to the remaining portfolios, in an attempt to weaken the revigorated Liberal opposition and consolidate a workable governing majority.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=369}} Despite successfully recruiting enough supporters from outside the party to form a government, the Cabinet was hobbled from the outset by its lack of internal unity. It was doomed when [[Jos<U+00E9> Tom<U+00E1>s Nabuco de Ara<U+00FA>jo]] delivered a speech advocating a merger of Moderate Conservatives and Liberals into a truly new political party.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|pp=374<U+2013>375}}

So enthusiastically well-received was this speech, that both groups voted together as a single, cohesive faction, leaving the government without a majority. The Cabinet requested that the Emperor dissolve the Chamber and call for new elections, but he refused. With no remaining alternative, Caxias and his ministers resigned, and on 24 May 1862 Pedro&nbsp;II named a member of the Moderate-Liberal coalition to form a new cabinet.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=376}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|pp=669<U+2013>670}} The new political party was called the "Progressive League".{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=378}} Barely a month later, Caxias's only son died suddenly at age 14 of an unknown disease.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=571}} There was a small consolation at the end of 1862 when, on 2 December, he was promoted to Marshal of the Army, the highest rank in the Brazilian army.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=571}}

==Paraguayan War==
{{main|Paraguayan War}}

===Siege of Uruguaiana===
In December 1864, the dictator of Paraguay, [[Francisco Solano L<U+00F3>pez]] took advantage of Brazil's military [[Uruguayan War|intervention in Uruguay]] to establish his country as a regional power. The [[Paraguayan army]] invaded the Brazilian province of [[Mato Grosso]] (currently the state of [[Mato Grosso do Sul]]), triggering the [[Paraguayan War]]. Four months later, Paraguayan troops invaded [[Argentina|Argentine]] territory in preparation for an attack upon the Brazilian province of [[Rio Grande do Sul]].{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=227}}

The situation in Rio Grande do Sul was chaotic and the local military commanders were incapable of mounting an effective resistance against the Paraguayan army. Pedro&nbsp;II, aware of the danger, decided to go to the front in person to shore up operations.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=228}} As the Emperor's military [[Aide-de-Camp]], Caxias followed his monarch into the combat zone.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=242}}{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=202}}

The Imperial party arrived in Rio Grande do Sul's capital, [[Porto Alegre]], in July 1865. From there, they traveled inland until they reached [[Uruguaiana]] in September.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=229-235}}{{sfn|Barman|1999|pp=202<U+2013>205}} The trip was an uneasy experience for Caxias. The Emperor's entourage also included the War Minister, <U+00C2>ngelo Ferraz (later the Baron of Uruguaiana). A member of the Progressive League still in power, Ferraz was a personal enemy of Caxias.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=737}}{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=242}} They loathed each other and, now forced to keep company, argued. Pedro&nbsp;II ignored the conflict and did not intervene to stop their quarrelling.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=202}}

The Emperor's behavior bothered Caxias. In the beginning he wrote that Pedro&nbsp;II "continues to treat me in the best way possible and does not listen to anyone else but me on military affairs, which has greatly annoyed Ferraz".{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=738}} However, days later he remarked: "He [Pedro&nbsp;II] only cares about himself, and no one else."{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=738}} Used to being the preeminent counsel in wartime, Caxias was undermined by his vanity and soon barely able to hide his displeasure at being overshadowed by another. A delighted Ferraz noticed: "Caxias is very sullen. In part he is right, but he has only himself to blame. One should never play the role of subordinate or valet in a place where one once was king."{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=325}}{{sfn|Vianna|1968|p=170}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=739}}

The Brazilian town of Uruguayana had been occupied by a Paraguayan army. By the time Caxias and his party arrived, the town was under siege by a combined force made up of Brazilian, Argentine and Uruguayan units<U+2014>the latter had allied with Brazil against Paraguay. The Paraguayans surrendered without further bloodshed, freeing the Emperor and Caxias to return to the Imperial capital.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=235-238}}{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=205}}

===Commander-in-Chief===
[[Image:House of caxias in tuyu cue.jpg|thumb|200px|left|alt=|House where Caxias lived in the abandoned Paraguayan village of Tuy<U+00FA> Cu<U+00E9>, c.1867]]
[[Image:Equipment and supply line of caxias.jpg|thumb|200px|left|alt=|Equipment and supply line of Caxias in Tuy<U+00FA> Cu<U+00E9>, c.1867]]
The Allies next invaded Paraguay in April 1866 and, after an initial success, their advance was blocked by fortifications at Humait<U+00E1>, which blocked further progress both by land and along the River Paraguay. A [[Battle of Curuz<U+00FA>|fort at Curuz<U+00FA>]] was taken initially, but an attempt on 22 September against [[Battle of Curupayty|Curupaiti]] was repulsed.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=210}} The failure to take Curupaiti caused the morale of the troops to reach its lowest point, and the Brazilian generals quarreled and could not agree on further action.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|pp=243<U+2013>244}}{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|pp=251<U+2013>252}}{{sfn|Salles|2003|p=86}} To address the situation, the Progressive cabinet decided to create a unified command over Brazilian land forces operating in Paraguay, and it turned to Caxias as the new head.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=244}}{{sfn|Salles|2003|p=86}}{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=252}}

The 63-year old Caxias was named Commander-in-Chief of Brazil's armies in Paraguay on 10 October 1866.{{sfn|Vianna|1968|p=174}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=234}} "Among the staff of the Armed Forces of the Empire", said historian Ricardo Salles, "only Caxias presented leadership and military competence to reorganize and encourage the [[Military organization|command structure]], regularize and improve the [[Military logistics|logistic basis]] of the army, infuse courage among the officer corps, adequately train and equip the soldiers for a long war in hostile terrain and against a warlike enemy."{{sfn|Salles|2003|p=87}} He explained to his wife that the reason he had accepted the post was because the war "was an evil that has reached more or less all, from the Emperor to the most unfortunate slave."{{sfn|Salles|2003|p=86}}

Caxias arrived in Paraguay on 17 November,{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=235}} and assumed, for all practical purposes, the supreme command of both land and naval forces in the war, even though he had not explicitly been given authority over the navy.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=278}} His first measure was to dismiss Vice-Admiral [[Joaquim Marques Lisboa, Marquis of Tamandar<U+00E9>|Joaquim Marques Lisboa]] (later the Marquis of Tamandar<U+00E9> and also member of the Progressive League) and appoint fellow Conservative, Vice-Admiral [[Joaquim Jos<U+00E9> In<U+00E1>cio, Viscount of Inha<U+00FA>ma|Joaquim Jos<U+00E9> In<U+00E1>cio]] (later the Viscount of Inha<U+00FA>ma), to lead the navy.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=253}} From October 1866 until July 1867, all offensive operations were suspended.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=284}} During this period, Caxias trained the soldiers, re-equipped the army with newer guns, improved the quality of the officer corps, and upgraded the health corps and overall hygiene of the troops, putting an end to epidemics.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|pp=280<U+2013>282}} [[Alfredo d'Escragnolle Taunay, Viscount of Taunay|Alfredo d'Escragnolle Taunay]] (later the Viscount of Taunay), who fought in the war, said that Caxias was a "generous military chief, who forgave small errors, but was implacable with those who commited grave misdeeds, or, then, who betrayed his confidence."{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=545}}

With the Brazilian army ready for combat, Caxias began the operation to encircle Humait<U+00E1> and force its capitulation by siege. The first move was made against the abandoned Paraguayan village of Tuy<U+00FA> Cu<U+00E9>, which was occupied on 29 July 1867.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|pp=297<U+2013>298}} The combined Brazilian-Argentine-Uruguayan army advanced through hostile territory in the effort to surround Humait<U+00E1>. When the Paraguayan position at Tah<U+00ED> was taken on 2 November, Humait<U+00E1> was completely cut off from overland reinforcement by Paraguayan forces.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=299}} On 19 February 1868, Brazilian ironclads successfully made a passage up the Paraguay river under heavy fire, assuming full control of the river and thus isolating Humait<U+00E1> from resupply by water.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|pp=321<U+2013>322}}

===''Dezembrada''===
[[Image:Caxias headquarters humaita.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=|Caxias' headquarters in Humait<U+00E1> fortress, after it was taken by the Allies, c.1868]]
[[Image:Caxias bodyguard in Paraguay.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=|The bodyguard of Caxias in Paraguay, c.1868]]
The relationship between the Marquis of Caxias<U+2014>now the Allied Commander-in-Chief<U+2014>and the governing Progressive cabinet worsened until it became a political crisis. Soon after Caxias was chosen to lead the Brazilian forces in 1866, Ferraz was relieved of the War ministry portfolio to avoid complications arising from the friction between the two men.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=245}}{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=253}} As time passed, Caxias became irritated by the constant criticisms directed at him by newspapers connected to the Progressives. He tendered his resignation, but the Progressive-led government refused to accept. Having lost credibility for prosecuting the war and plagued by party infighting, the Progressive Cabinet resigned. The Emperor called the Conservatives back into power on 16 July 1868.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|pp=247<U+2013>256}}{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|pp=335<U+2013>336}}

Meanwhile in Paraguay, Caxias continued prosecuting the siege of Humait<U+00E1>. To prevent the annihilation of the troops defending the fortress, L<U+00F3>pez managed to engineer a successful withdrawal of all Paraguayan troops by 24 July without being detected by Allied forces. The allies occupied the Paraguayan stronghold on the following day without firing a shot. The Conservatives had returned to power a few days before Humait<U+00E1> was taken, although Caxias only learned of this later .{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|pp=329<U+2013>330}}

Pressing his advantage, the Marquis began organizing an assault on the new Paraguayan defenses which L<U+00F3>pez had thrown up along the Pikysyry, south of [[Asunci<U+00F3>n]] (Paraguay's capital). This stream afforded a strong defensive position which was anchored to the northwest by the [[Paraguay River|R<U+00ED>o Paraguay]] and on the southeast by the swampy jungle of the [[Chaco (Paraguay)|Chaco region]], both of which were considered to be nearly impassible by a large force. By the last part of September, the allied armies were facing the entrenched Paraguayan forces at the Pikysyry. Rather than making a frontal attack on L<U+00F3>pez's line, Caxias had a road cut through the [[Chaco (Paraguay)|Chaco region]].{{sfn|Thompson|1869|p=279}} The road was finished, undetected by L<U+00F3>pez by early December, allowing the Allied forces to outflank the Paraguayan lines and attack from the rear.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=223}} In three successive battles ([[Battle of Ytoror<U+00F3>|Ytoror<U+00F3>]], [[Battle of Avay|Avay]] and [[Battle of Lomas Valentinas|Lomas Valentinas]]), which became known as ''Dezembrada'', the combined Allied forces completely annihilated the Paraguayan army. L<U+00F3>pez himself barely managed to escape with a few followers,{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|pp=360<U+2013>374}}{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=223}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=250-266}} and on 1 January 1869, the Brazilians occupied Asunci<U+00F3>n.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=384}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=266}}

The Marquis had to take great risks to accomplish those victories. In the Ytoror<U+00F3> engagement, which occurred on 5 December, the Allied objective was to take a bridge over Ytoror<U+00F3> river. Several attempts were made cross the bridge, but each was repelled by intense fire from the Paraguayan positions. In a final attempt, the Brazilian soldiers panicked and began to flee in disorder. Caxias, witnesseing the impending disaster, unsheathed his sword and charged on horseback toward the bridge, followed by his staff. He passed through the fleeing troops shouting "Long live His Majesty", "Long Live Brazil" and finally, "Those who are true Brazilians follow me!"{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=366}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=252}} The display stopped the retreat immediately, allowed the units to regroup and, in a vigorous attack led personally by Caxias, overwhelmed the Paraguayan positions.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=366}}{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|pp=253<U+2013>254}}

The Brazilian army's low morale and unwillingness to engage forced the Marquis to personally head "the assault, in a suicide move in which, surprisingly, he survived", said historian Francisco Doratioto.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=368}} Doratioto also states that had "Caxias been hit when he crossed the bridge, as happened to other officers, almost certainly the army would have dispersed, run away in disorder, which would have had unpredictable consequences in the development of the war."{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=366}} Several men who were next to the Commander-in-Chief during the attack were killed, as well as his own horse.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=366}} The loss of fighting spirit among the troops was a result, according to Caxias, of the long duration of the war, the lack of enough capable officers who could provide role models to their men and, most importantly, the existence of former slaves among the ranks. They had been freed to fight in the war, but were often insubordinate, and the Marquis deduced that this occurred because they were "men who do not comprehend what is fatherland, society and family; who still regard themselves as slaves, but who have only changed masters."{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=367}}

===Aftermath===
[[Image:Building in asuncion where caxias lived 1870.png|thumb|200px|left|alt=|Building in [[Asunci<U+00F3>n]], capital of [[Paraguay]], where Caxias lived after having taken the city, c.1869]]
Caxias was growing old, and was ill and exhausted by the time he reached Asunci<U+00F3>n. As he did not feel up to the task of pursuing L<U+00F3>pez into the Paraguayan hinterland, he asked to be either relieved of his post or to take a short leave in order to recover. Many of the officers in Brazil's Paraguayan force had become casualties during the previous year, and it was thought that the presence of the Commander-in-Chief was necessary. Although his request was denied, Caxias appointed a senior member of his staff as acting-commander and left for Brazil on 19 January 1869.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=225}} The Emperor was angered that the Marquis had left his post without permission, and especially that Caxias had declared the war to have been already won<U+2014>even though L<U+00F3>pez was still at large and regrouping his remaining military assets. With victory having been thus declared, Caxias's subordinates began preparing for what they assumed would be an imminent return to Brazil. The lack of will to follow-up on the Allied victories seriously endangered the hard-won achievements of the past months, even as the objective of eliminating L<U+00F3>pez as a threat remained tantalizingly within reach.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=225}}

The Marquis arrived unannounced in Rio de Janeiro in early February.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=246}} He went directly to his home, to the surprise of his wife, who<U+2014>like everyone else<U+2014>was not aware that he had returned.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=246}} He remained at home for a month, refusing to leave.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=246}} Pedro II was greatly disappointed in Caxias, though he was also very aware that the Marquis was the person most responsible for the great successes during the war and that these accomplishments had come at the cost of years of sacrifice and personal bravery. The Emperor called the Marquis to the Imperial Palace, the [[Pa<U+00E7>o de S<U+00E3>o Crist<U+00F3>v<U+00E3>o]], on 21 February 1869 and they reconciled.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=226}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=797}}

A few days later, Caxias was awarded the [[Order of Pedro I]] and was raised from marquis to duke, the highest rank in Brazilian nobility. These were distinctions that no other individual received during the long, 58-year reign of Pedro II.{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=246}} Historian Heitor Lyra said that "the title of Duke gave Caxias incalculable prestige. It overshadowed, to a certain extent, its own designation [Caxias], already by itself glorious. He became, from that point, ''the Duke''. There was no necessity to say his name. The title was enough<U+2014>the Duke. The Duke, in Brazil, was him, could be only him, as ''the Duke'', in England of [[George IV of the United Kingdom|George IV]], could only be [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Wellington]]."{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=246}}

Nonetheless, this did not shelter him from being subjected to attacks and accusations<U+2014>some petty<U+2014>from Liberals in Parliament, including for having left his post without permission.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|pp=390<U+2013>391}} The embittered Duke wrote to Os<U+00F3>rio: "When I was young, my friend, I did not know how to explain the reason why the elderly were selfish, but now that I am old, I see that they are like that because of the disappointments and ingratitudes they suffer during their lives. At least this is what happens to me".{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=391}} To historian Francisco Doratioto, the "attacks on Caxias were exaggerated. In Paraguay, he was a successful and competent commander, who made mistakes, it is true, but who never lost a campaign. [...] If some of these criticisms had arisen from strictly military aspects of the performance of this general, most were from political motivation, made by liberals, or even caused from personal envy."{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=392}}

==Later years==
===Figurehead presidency===
[[Image:Joaquim da Rocha Fragoso - Duque de Caxias, 1875.png|thumb|200px|right|alt=|The Duke of Caxias at age 71, 1875]]
Jos<U+00E9> Paranhos, now Viscount of Rio Branco, led a cabinet which lasted from 1871 to 1875. Although the government was quite successful,{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|pp=711, 851, 857}} two serious crises arose that challenged its viability and undermined the foundations of the monarchy itself. The first was resulted from the controversy over the [[Law of Free Birth]], which emancipated children born to slave women after its enactment. With half of its members supporting the law and the other half staunchly opposed, a serious rift was opened within the Conservative Party. The opponents represented the interests of powerful coffee farmers.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=261}}

The second crisis developed after the government entered into a conflict with two bishops who had ordered [[Freemasonry|Freemasons]] expelled from [[lay brother]]hoods. The dispute grew out of proportion when both bishops were convicted and given prison sentences for having disobeyed the government's order to rescind their expulsions of Freemasons.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=257}} As Catholicism was the state religion, the Emperor exercised, with the Papacy's acquiescence, a great deal of control over Church affairs<U+2014>paying clerical salaries, appointing parish priests, nominating bishops, ratifying papal bulls, and overseeing seminaries.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=254}} As a result of the furor over the handling of the affair, Rio Branco and his cabinet resigned, "disunited and weary after four years in office", according to historian Roderick J. Barman.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=269}} Pedro II asked Caxias to form a new cabinet. The duke later gave a remarkable account of their meeting:

{{quote|Believe that when I entered my carriage to go S<U+00E3>o Crist<U+00F3>v<U+00E3>o, summoned by the emperor, I was determined not to accept. But he, as soon as he saw me, embraced me and said to me that he would not let me go unless I told him that I would accept the post of minister and that, if I refused to do this service, he would summon the Liberals and would have to tell everybody that I was responsible for the consequence, all the while encircling me with his arms. I pointed out to him my circumstances, my age, and my infirmity; but he concurred in nothing. To free myself from him, I should have had to shove him off, and this I could not do. I bowed my head and said that I would do what he wanted but that I was sure that he would have cause for regret, since I would not be minister for long, because I would die from work and troubles. However, he listened to nothing and told me that I should only do what I could do but that I must not abandon him, since he would in that case abandon us and go away.{{sfn|Barman|1999|pp=269<U+2013>270}}{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=247}}}}

The elderly Caxias, nearly 72 and widowed since 1874, was in poor health and could only serve as a figurehead president of the government which was created on 25 June 1875.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=269}} According to Roderick J. Barman, for "the new cabinet to possess any energy and direction, it needed to include a senior politician of force and standing. The emperor turned to the [[Jo<U+00E3>o Maur<U+00ED>cio Wanderley, Baron of Cotejipe|baron of Cotejipe]]", who had been Caxias' colleague in the Conciliation cabinet back in the 1850s, to fill the role of ''de facto'' president.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=270}}{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=857}} The Caxias-Cotejipe cabinet attempted to placate the discord created by the previous cabinet. Their measures included financial aide to coffee farmers, an amnesty for the convicted bishops, and the selection of new ministers and a call for elections to please the pro-slavery Conservatives.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=862}} Caxias, who was a Freemason himself but also a staunch Catholic, threatened to resign if the emperor did not grant the amnesty, which Pedro II grudgingly issued in September 1875.{{sfn|Lyra|1977b|pp=217<U+2013>218}}

===Death===
[[Image:Duke of caxias 1877.jpg|thumb|200px|left|alt=|Caxias around the age 74, c.1877]]
"I think like you that a new political situation it is coming soon. The ministry is a corpse that Caxias, despite all his glories and importance that he holds in the emperor's mind, will not be able to revitalize. The ministry lives only because of Caxias' name", wrote the liberal Nabuco de Ara<U+00FA>jo to a party colleague in December 1878.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=929}} According to Roderick J. Barman, the "duke of Caxias was too old and too sick to provide leadership". His health problems became so troubling{{sfn|Barman|1999|pp=285<U+2013>286}} that he repeatedly to resign beginning in early 1876.{{sfn|Lyra|1977b|p=265}} At the end of 1877, Pedro&nbsp;II paid a visit to Caxias and ascertained that he could no longer stay in office{{sfn|Lyra|1977b|p=266}} and called the liberals to form a new cabinet on 1 January 1878.{{sfn|Nabuco|1975|p=929}}

Caxias was not only afflicted by concerns over his declining health, but increasingly felt a sense of alienation. The duke no longer saw himself playing a relevant role in politics.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=33}} He belonged to an older generation who perceived the Emperor (and consequently, the monarchy) as being an essential factor in holding the nation together.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=317}} The new politicians who had begun to dominate the government had little memory of times before Pedro&nbsp;II assumed control in 1840. Unlike their predecessors, had no experience of the Regency and early years of Pedro&nbsp;II's reign, when external and internal dangers threatened the nation's existence. They had only known a stable administration and prosperity.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=317}} The young politicians saw no reason to uphold and defend the Imperial office as a unifying force beneficial to the nation.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=318}}

Times were changing fast, and Caxias was aware of the situation. He became increasingly nostalgic for the old times he had spent with his now-dead Conservative Party colleagues and held pessimistic views of future political prospects.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=556}} When [[Joaquim Rodrigues Torres, Viscount of Itabora<U+00ED>]]<U+2014>one of the last survivors of those conservative leaders who had begun their careers during the 1830s<U+2014>died in 1872, the duke wrote to a friend: "Who will replace him? I dont know, I cannot see... The vacuum he left will not be filled, as it was not with Eus<U+00E9>bio, [[Hon<U+00F3>rio Carneiro Le<U+00E3>o, Marquis of Paran<U+00E1>|Paran<U+00E1>]], [[Paulino Soares de Sousa, 1st Viscount of Uruguai|Uruguai]], Manuel Felizardo and many others who helped us sustain this little church [i.e., the monarchy, his "second faith"], collapsed or almost collapsed on 7 April 1831."{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=556}}

Confined to a wheel chair as his health slowly declined, the Duke of Caxias lived his remaining days at his Santa M<U+00F4>nica farm, located in the countryside of Rio de Janeiro province.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=288-290}} On 7 May 1880 at 11 p.m.,{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1208}} he quietly died, attended by members of his family.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|pp=290<U+2013>292}} A saddened Pedro&nbsp;II (who visited Caxias several times during his long illness) remarked about his "friend of almost a half century", that he had "known him, and esteemed him since 1832. He was 76, almost 77-years old. And so we remain in this world."{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1209}} After a huge funeral procession, Caxias was buried in the ''S<U+00E3>o Francisco de Paula'' cemetery in the city of Rio de Janeiro.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=293}} On 25 August 1949, his remains, as well as those of his wife, were exhumed and reinterred in Rio de Janeiro's the Duke of Caxias Pantheon.{{sfn|Souza|2008|pp=27<U+2013>28}}

==Legacy==
[[Image:Monumento ao Duque de Caxias, de Victor Brecheret 01.JPG|thumb|250px|right|alt=|Monument in honor of the Duke of Caxias in the city of [[S<U+00E3>o Paulo]]]]
At the time of his death in 1880 until the 1920s the Duke of Caxias was not regarded as the most important military historical character in Brazilian history. This place belonged to [[Manuel Lu<U+00ED>s Os<U+00F3>rio, Marquis of Erval]].{{sfn|Castro|2002|p=15}}{{sfn|Doratioto|2008|pp=15, 21}} Caxias was barely remembered.{{sfn|Castro|2002|p=16}} His memory was slowly recovered and the first attempt happened in 1923 when the ministry of the Army created an annual celebration in honor of Caxias.{{sfn|Castro|2002|p=17}} In 1925 his birthday became officially the "Day of the Soldier", which commemorates the Brazilian Army.{{sfn|Castro|2002|p=17}}{{sfn|Doratioto|2008|p=21}} On 13 March 1962 Caxias became ''Patrono'' (literally, "Patron", a kind of "patron saint") of the Brazilian Army, making him the most important figure in the army tradition.{{sfn|Doratioto|2008|p=21}} According to Adriana Barreto de Souza,{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=28}} Francisco Doratioto{{sfn|Doratioto|2008|p=22}} and Celso Castro{{sfn|Castro|2002|p=20}} the Duke of Caxias took the place of Os<U+00F3>rio because he was seen as a loyal and dutiful officer who could serve as a role model in the Brazilian republic plagued since its birth in 1889 by military insubordination, rebellions and coups d'<U+00C9>tat.

The historiography is often positive toward Caxias. Since the first well known biography published in 1878 he "has been the subject of several hagiographic biographies", according to historian Roderick J. Barman.{{sfn|Barman|1988|p=298}} Nelson Werneck Sodr<U+00E9> said that Caxias, as a historical character, suffers from the same shortcomings as Pedro II. Both have been always presented as irreproachable men. Not that the historian regards them as unworthy, but to him somewhere in the process the human face of each was lost, giving place to "this black and white figure, model of individual virtues".{{sfn|Sodr<U+00E9>|2004|p=134}}

Nonetheless, to Sodr<U+00E9> Caxias was "not only the greatest military commander of his continent [South America], in his time, but [also] a great politician".{{sfn|Sodr<U+00E9>|2004|p=137}} Moreover, the Duke of Caxias was "<U+2014>more than D. Pedro II<U+2014>the Empire." His respect to the law and his [[Civilian control of the military|complete obedience to the civilian government]] were fundamental. "Caxias, who could have been the most powerful [[caudillo]]," says Sodr<U+00E9>, "exempts the country of caudillism. While, in the [[R<U+00ED>o de la Plata]], the [[Justo Jos<U+00E9> de Urquiza|Urquizas]], the [[Juan Manuel de Rosas|Rosas]], the [[Manuel Oribe|Oribes]], caused disaster to their nations and hindered their development, Caxias added to his prestige both his roles in the consolidation of the empire as well in its external victories without ever throwing his sword over the political balance nor taking [by force] political offices for himself."{{sfn|Sodr<U+00E9>|2004|pp=135<U+2013>136}}

According to Francisco Doratioto, the duke "was uncompromising in the defense of the established order, but, once obtained the military vantage over the rebels, he attempted to reach a conciliation, avoiding inhuman treatment toward the prisioners and granting them amnesty". Also, in "his conception the military power was subordinated to the civilian power, and the greatness of the country was associated with to the order and to the established authorities",{{sfn|Doratioto|December 2003|p=63}} something quite different from his Hispanic-American counterparts, as well of the Brazilian military of the late Empire and most of the republican era. The historian remarked as well that:

{{cquotetxt|The official military historiography avoided making critical references to the command of Caxias in Paraguay,{{ref label|specialnotes7|G|none}} or, yet, in relation to other moments of his career. It tried to build a pure historical icon, without flaws, many times belittling his contemporaries ([[Bartolom<U+00E9> Mitre|Mitre]] and [[Manuel Lu<U+00ED>s Os<U+00F3>rio, Marquis of Erval|Os<U+00F3>rio]], for example), as it was necessary to diminish other military commanders to greaten the figure of the duke, until turning him into the Patron of the Army. The artificiality of such creation results in the little empathy from the part of the ordinary citizen for the icon. Caxias in Paraguay had doubts, pride, resentment, and made mistakes; in short, he was a real character, just as the author or reader of this book. Caxias, however, was able to rise above his limitations, imposed on himself great personal sacrifices and incorporated the responsibility of accomplishing the objective [...]. In this context, Caxias was, indeed, a hero; he carried with him, it is true, social and political prejudice of his time, but one can not demand from the past the observance of present-day values.|Francisco Doratioto{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|pp=392<U+2013>393}}}}

Ricardo Salles said that although his character "evidenced a conservative mind, typical of a dominant group of a socially hierarchical society divided by slavery, there is no reason to deduce based on that he conducted the army without regard to reduce to the maximum the human losses, in battle or by diseases". "On the contrary", affirmed the historian, "the military behavior of Caxias, as it was expected from a competent commander, was guided by an adequate preparation of his actions, always carefully planned and executed [...]". He concluded: "A man of his time, [...] Caxias fulfilled his duty."{{sfn|Salles|2003|p=87}}

Roderick J. Barman affirmed that Caxias was not only "extremely powerful in the Conservative party",{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=219}} but also "the country's most distinguished"{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=202}} and "most successful soldier"{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=211}} that "himself had proved his capacity and his loyalty by defeating revolts against the regime"{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=88}} C. H. Haring said that he was "a brilliant army officer", also "Brazil's most famous military figure"{{sfn|Haring|1969|p=49}} and a man "who was genuinely loyal to the throne"{{sfn|Haring|1969|p=131}} H<U+00E9>lio Vianna regarded Caxias as "the greatest soldier of Brazil".{{sfn|Vianna|1968|p=177}} To Thomas Whigham, the duke was "destined to occupy a lofty spot in Brazil's national mythology. He often had to act as a statesman as much as military man" and was "[s]hrewdly competent in both roles".{{sfn|Whigham|2002|p=62}}

==Titles and honors==
[[Image:COA Duke of Caxias.svg|thumb|180px|right|Arms of the Duke of Caxias]]

===Titles of nobility===
* Baron (without [[Grandee|Greatness]]) on 18 July 1841.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=569}}
* Count on 25 March 1845.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=72}}
* Marquis on 26 June 1852.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=570}}
* Duke on 23 March 1869.{{sfn|Doratioto|2002|p=570}}{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=571}}

===Other titles===
* Member of the Brazilian [[Privy Council|Council of State]].{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Member of the [[Brazilian Historic and Geographic Institute]].{{sfn|Vianna|1968|p=223}}
* Emperor's war counselor.{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Emperor's [[Aide-de-Camp]].{{sfn|Lyra|1977a|p=242}}
* Emperor's [[gentleman usher]].{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}

===Honours===
* Grand Cross of the Brazilian [[Order of the Southern Cross]].{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Grand Cross of the Brazilian [[Order of the Rose]].{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Grand Cross of the Brazilian [[Order of Pedro I]].{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Grand Cross of the Brazilian [[Order of Saint Benedict of Aviz]].{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Grand Cross of the Portuguese [[Order of the Immaculate Conception of Vila Vi<U+00E7>osa]].{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}

===Military honours===
* Medal (oval) of the Independence War (Bahia).{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Medal of the army in the Oriental State of Uruguay in 1852.{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Commemorative medal of the surrender of the division of the army of Paraguay that occupied the village of Uruguaiana.{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Medal (oval) of bravery "to the bravest ones" (1867).{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}
* Medal awarded to the army, armada and to civil servants in operations in the Paraguayan War (1870).{{sfn|Cardoso|1880|p=33}}

==Notes==
{{refbegin|colwidth=30em}}
<ol style="list-style:upper-alpha">
<li>{{note label|specialnotes1|A|none}}The family name was "Lima da Silva". After the birth of the Duke of Caxias all members changed the name to "Lima e Silva".{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=107}}</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes2|B|none}}In 1846 Jos<U+00E9> Joaquim de Lima (Caxias' uncle) claimed noble ancestry for his family, making connections that went as far as to the [[Visigoths|Visigothic]] as well as to [[Kingdom of Le<U+00F3>n|Leonese]] monarchs. Historian Adriana Barreto de Souza said that although it might be true, by the 18th century the family had long lost its noble status. Thus, their achievements at the 19th century owned solely to their efforts, not due to a possible illustrious ancestry.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=553}}</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes3|C|none}}The disciplines in the '''1st year''' of the Royal Military Academy were: arithmetic, algebra, geometry, trigonometry and technical drawing. Of the '''2nd year''': (algebra, geometry, analytical geometry, differential and integral calculus, descriptive geometry and technical drawing. Of the '''3rd year''': (mechanics, ballistics and technical drawing. Of the '''5th''' year: [[Military tactics|tactics]], strategy, camping, fortification in campaign, terrain reconnaissance and chemistry. Lima e Silva dropped from the academy before taking classes in the '''4th year'''.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=113}}</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes4|D|none}}All that is known is that Lima e Silva signed the minutes of a meeting among officers of the Right and Center Brigades who had decided to send a delegation to their Commander-in-Chief, [[Pierre Labatut]], to plead him to reconcile with officers of the Left Brigade with whom he had become estranged. The meeting had barely ended when two officers of the Left Brigade arrived giving the news that Labatut had been arrested.{{sfn|Souza|2008|p=131}} To historian Affonso de Carvalho, Lima e Silva, whose name is the last in the minutes, signed under protest and felt uncomfortable with the idea of sending a delegation to talk with the commander-in-chief. Taking a part in a plot to remove Labatut from the command and arrest him is even more unlikely.{{sfn|Carvalho|1976|p=19}}</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes7|G|none}}On the opposite direction is the marxist historiography that appeared in the 1960s and 1970s in Latin America. Although largely discredited nowadays, this historiography achieved great success in this time period. Its most well known Brazilian historian "portrayed the conflict as a genocide deliberately perpetrated against the Paraguayan people and Brazil's slave and Afro-Brazilian populations."{{sfn|Kraay and Whigham|2004|p=18}} Historians Hendrik Kraay and Thomas Whigham called it an "improbable assertion".{{sfn|Kraay and Whigham|2004|p=18}} Against Caxias the most serious allegation was that in a letter supposedly written by him he told that he had "deliberately spread cholera in Corrientes and other [Argentine] provinces hostile to the war effort by having infected corpses thrown into the rivers."{{sfn|Kraay and Whigham|2004|p=18}} Historians Hendrik Kraay, Thomas Whigham{{sfn|Kraay and Whigham|2004|p=18}} and Ricardo Salles{{sfn|Salles|2003|p=87}}dismissed this allegation since there is no proof of the existence of such letter. Lastly, "no evidence that Brazilian commanders deliberately used back men as cannon fodder has come to light, and the number of slaves forced into the army and navy was quite small (about seven thousand)".{{sfn|Kraay and Whigham|2004|p=18}}</li>
</ol>
{{refend}}

